Like all plants, crops take up nitrates from the soil as they grow. But crops are
harvested, rather than being left to die and decompose, so the nitrogen they
contain isn’t returned to the soil. Over time, the nitrogen content of the soil
decreases, leading to poor crop growth and deciency diseases. So farmers
have ways of increasing the amount of nitrates in the soil to help their crops
Spreading animal manure or compost on elds recycles the nutrients left in
plant and animal waste and returns them to the soil through decomposition.
Articial fertilisers containing nitrates (and other mineral ions needed by
plants) can also be used, but these can be expensive.
This is where, instead of growing the same crop in a eld year after year,
different crops are grown each year in a cycle. The cycle usually includes a
nitrogen-xing crop (e.g. peas or beans), which helps to put nitrates back into
the soil for another crop to use the following year.
